y, to 1980 when it had emerged as a global technological and economic power, Lee highlights the role of indigenous techniques in modern science as it took shape in Japan. In doing so, she reveals how knowledge of microbes lay at the heart of some of Japan’s most prominent technological breakthroughs in the global economy. At a moment when twenty-first-century developments in the fields of antibiotic resistance, the microbiome, and green chemistry suggest that the traditional eradication-based approach to the microbial world is unsustainable, twentieth-century Japanese microbiology provides a new, broader vantage for understanding and managing microbial interactions with society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFermentation. 0aMicrobiologyzJapan. 0aMicrobiology-Japan. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afermentation science, microbial world, indigenous industry, traditional industry, applied science, twentieth-century Japan, biotechnology, craft, industrialization, microbiology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391900 cprintz978022681274840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226812885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226812885/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-07